<title>FINLAND: NOKIA SAYS JOINS NEW PDA STANDARD DEAL.</title>
<headline>NOKIA SAYS JOINS NEW PDA STANDARD DEAL.</headline>
<dateline>HELSINKI 1997-06-23</dateline>
<text>
<p>Finnish telecoms group Nokia Oy said on Monday it had joined an agreement with U.S. and Japanese computer firms to form a common set of standards for building mobile network computers, or personal digital assistants (PDAs).</p>
<p>Nokia's mobile phones unit is among companies including Fujitsu, IBM, Netscape and Toshiba, which are fixing standards for the devices.</p>
<p>The companies said in a statement the devices would range from &quot;smart&quot; cellular phones to lightweight, hand-held mobile devices with easy access to the Internet or corporate networks.</p>
<p>Nokia spokesman Lauri Kivinen called the deal more a working group than an alliance.</p>
<p>He said it offered long-term benefit to Nokia since it involved communication in a mobile environment, core for the Finnish company, and set a standard in which Nokia was included.</p>
<p>Nokia has no plans to start making mobile network computers itself, he added.</p>
